tickets.description:
NetSurf seems to display redundant attributes in tags rather than just ignoring them. For example, this HTML fragment is taken from a forum:

&lt;html&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign="top" height="100%"&gt;
&lt;font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2" color="\#0e0e0e"&gt;
&lt;span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"&gt; Anyone read it yet?  Any good?  
Anyone read it who wasn't a fan?  I want info people\!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;ahh, 
this whole month ahead thing throws me off.  You do have it in the UK 
now, right?
&lt;/span id="msg"&gt;
&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

The &lt;/SPAN&gt; tag should not have a 'id=msg' attribute, but it would be better if NetSurf just disregarded the redudant code and closed the &lt;SPAN&gt; tag: at present it treats it as text and displays it.

Chris Wraight
email@lym.iconbar.com

With
&lt;OL&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;FONT COLOR=RED&gt;Item 1&lt;/FONT&gt;
&lt;LI&gt;&lt;FONT COLOR=RED&gt;Item 2&lt;/FONT&gt;
&lt;/OL&gt;
The ordinals \(the "1" and "2"\) show as black and the list items show as red.  I believe the FONT attribute should apply to the ordinal as well as the list item.  I first noticed the problem with &lt;FONT SIZE="+1"&gt; where I found the size difference between the ordinal and the list item particularly noticeable \(and annoying\).

Putting the FONT attribute outside the OL tag works as required but is not valid HTML..  Putting the FONT attribute around the LI also works but the ordinal numbering goes wrong.  As this is also not valid HTML I do not think the wrong ordering matters.

Richard Wheeler

