Originator: NO

I've been experimenting and have discovered that including a link to a style sheet in an HTML page provokes this bug consistently, but only when the page is served from WebJames running on the same machine.

This leads me to suspect it's some sort of blocking issue ... perhaps NetSurf is blocking waiting for some input, which a server running on the same machine can't provide until it gets polled in, of course.

Whether this is the fault of NetSurf, WebJames or RISC OS I do now know :\) But the 8 April 2007 build of NetSurf doesn'r show this behaviour.

This HTML page triggers the bug, but if the link to the stylesheet is removed the problem goes away.

&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;
&lt;link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/include/head-styles"/&gt;
&lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body bgcolor="\#ddddff"&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;

tickets.description:
From: Christopher Martin &lt;belles@internode.on.net&gt;

I am using version 2.0 \(Dev\) \(20 Aug 2007 02:45\) r3529. But as I recall, this has been a long-standing bug. According to the User Guide, a Shift+Adjust click on a link should allow saving the target address as a URL. However, the behaviour is the same as that produced by plain Adjust, as if the Shift key status is being ignored.

Tonight, I downloaded the latest sources via SVN. I think I may have identified the cause of the problem. There is a block of code in function browser\_window\_mouse\_action\_html\(...\), in file &lt;netsurf.desktop.c.browser&gt;, in which three if-else tests are performed. The order of the tests is significant. The present order is as follows:

if \(mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_1 && mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_MOD\_1\) \{  ... \} else if \(mouse & \(BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_1 | BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_2\)\) \{  ... \} else if \(mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_2 && mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_MOD\_1\) \{  ... \}

Might I suggest you consider swapping the 2nd and 3rd tests so that the structure becomes:

if \(mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_1 && mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_MOD\_1\) \{  ... \} else if \(mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_2 && mouse & BROWSER\_MOUSE\_MOD\_1\) \{  ... \} else if \(mouse & \(BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_1 | BROWSER\_MOUSE\_CLICK\_2\)\) \{  ... \}

I have attached a modified version of &lt;netsurf.desktop.c.browser&gt; for your consideration. \(I should mention that I do not yet have all the tools needed to build Netsurf for myself and test my changes.\)

posts.text:
Logged In: NO 

From: Christopher Martin &lt;belles@internode.on.net&gt;

I have now recompiled Netsurf and the changes outlined do indeed solve the problem.

